  <section aria-labelledby="included">
    <h2 id="included">What's included</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>PowerShell helpers</strong> for local environment hygiene, repo setup, and repeatable actions.</li>
      <li><strong>CI/CD snippets</strong> for GitHub Actions + Vercel workflows (checks, caching, safe deploys).</li>
      <li><strong>Templates</strong> for YAML/config patterns you can reuse across projects.</li>
      <li><strong>Operational runbooks</strong> and sanity-check playbooks for calm shipping.</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="muted">
      Tip: keep scripts under <code>/tools</code> or <code>/scripts</code>, and treat them like product code:
      versioned, documented, and used through named actions.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <!-- Workflow: adds the missing â€œstory + depthâ€ layer -->
  <section aria-labelledby="workflow">
    <h2 id="workflow">The daily workflow (boring-but-powerful)</h2>
    <p>
      Hereâ€™s the repeatable loop I use for content, docs, and automation updates â€” the same logic applies
      whether youâ€™re writing a post, adding a page, or shipping a release.
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Create</strong> the change (page/post/script) in a clean, predictable folder path.</li>
      <li><strong>Validate</strong> structure and metadata (links, slugs, tags, indexes) before you ship.</li>
      <li><strong>Preview</strong> locally so you catch issues before they hit production.</li>
      <li><strong>Release</strong> in a batch when itâ€™s ready (changelog, versioning, clean history).</li>
      <li><strong>Deploy</strong> with the correct environment settings and a known-good baseline.</li>
    </ol>

    <p class="muted">
      The goal is not â€œmore automation.â€ The goal is fewer surprises.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <!-- Guardrails: the â€œfavorite pageâ€ feel -->
  <section aria-labelledby="guardrails">
    <h2 id="guardrails">Guardrails (when mistakes are expensive)</h2>
    <p>
      These are the safety patterns that keep production stable and recovery fast. If something goes wrong,
      you should be able to return to a known-good state quickly.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Pre-ship checks:</strong> catch broken links, collisions, and missing metadata early.</li>
      <li><strong>Point-in-time restore:</strong> maintain a reference build/tag you can always revert to.</li>
      <li><strong>Safe history operations:</strong> avoid unrecoverable mistakes when rebasing or rewriting.</li>
      <li><strong>Release discipline:</strong> ship in clean batches with a changelog and predictable diffs.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

